    "explanation": "As we know from Question 2.14, European call and put options are monotone increasing in volatility, so if we use the lower volatility we will underprice the option. Which volatility do we use? The choice becomes clear when we think about how we would actually hedge the short position in this option. We will assume we are in the Black-Scholes world and therefore will dynamically (or at least daily) hedge our option position. Due to the frequent hedging we are exposed to daily volatility and we must use the 20% volatility to price the option.\n\nha\n\n2, OPTION PRICING the approximation that the payoff is linear between Ky and Ko and use the techniques discussed in Question 2.38 our replicating portfolio will contain e 1/K, zero coupon bonds expiring at time T; : : : - (1/K2)-(1/Fa). e acall option struck at A, with notional a = Kook, > and e and a call option struck at K2 with notional - a. This approximation will be good for K, close to Ke, but will deteriorate as the two values of K are further apart. There are two ways to improve our replication. We can either select a finite number of points in the interior and then do piecewise straight lines between them, or we can write the payoff as a continuous super-position of options. In the second case, we have an uncountably infinite number of options but can replicate precisely. The key is that the second derivative of a call option with respect to strike is a delta function. Here are some possible related questions: e@ What is the final stock value that will result in the maximum error from our replicating portfolio? What is the error? e Improve the approximation of the replicating portfolio between Ky and Ko. e Say you can no longer trade zero coupon bonds. Change the replicating portfolio below Ky using only vanilla options. O 2.3.4. The Greeks.",
