    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "Jf the coin is fair then the number of heads in a row before you flip has no affect on the probability of another head so the answer is 1/2. If the interviewer flips 100 heads in a row, then it is unlikely that the coin is fair since the probability of this happening is 2\\sim !. In fact, in that case the most likely cause is that the coin is double-headed. To properly answer this question, we really need a prior distribution: what is our view that the coin is fair before we receive any information? Given we are in an interview and the interviewer may play tricks on us, let's say that we estimate that the coin is double-headed with p = 1% probability before we receive any information. This is a Bayesian approach to the problem, and we can apply Bayes' theorem. In fact, we are back in the situation of Question 3.10, and we can proceed in the same fashion. The probability that the coin is double-headed after N heads and no tails is PO p+(1 - p)2-N After 100 throws this will be very close to 1 for any reasonable p. You might mention that this problem comes up in the play “Rosencrantz and Guildenstern are dead” by Tom Stoppard. If you do not know this play, it is very funny and there is a great film version. It is based on two minor characters from “Hamlet.”\n\nHere are some possible related questions: e Do you think that people are Bayesians? e At what N would you get suspicious? (e.g. when would you be 99% sure that the coin is fixed?) e Suppose the coin instead of always tossing heads, alternated in such a way to give the sequence HTHTHTHTHAT... what then? O",
