    "promptEn": "Assume the stock price process 5$S_t$ follows the stochastic differential equation with a,o and yp > 0. What sort of qualitative behaviour does the stock price exhibit? What is the impact of the parameters a and 4? What effects do they have on the price of a call option on this stock?",
    "promptZh": "Assume the stock price process 5$S_t$ follows the stochastic differential equation with a,o and yp > 0. What sort of qualitative behaviour does the stock price exhibit? What is the impact of the parameters a and 4? What effects do they have on the price of a call option on this stock?",
    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "This process is a mean-reverting process. Why? If the stock price is above js, then the drift term will be negative, making the trend of the process downwards, and toward the level yz. If the stock price is below y, the drift term is positive and the process again moves toward py. Thus whatever level the process is at, the general trend is to head back to the level py, and we cail this trait mean reversion (with mean level yz). The size of the parameter a affects the size of the drift when the stock price is a given level away from the mean y. Thus it affects the rate of the mean reversion. The drift term of the process has no impact on the price of a call option, since we know that under the correct pricing measure we need the discounted stock price to have zero drift. This is achieved by changing the drift of the original process, rendering any initial drift term irrelevant. Here are some possible related questions: e What stochastic differential equation does the process X; = S? follow? e For the geometric Brownian motion process Y; following the stochastic differential equation dY, = pY,dt + oY,dW;, what effect do the parameters ys and o have? e The Bessel process R; of dimension 3 follows the stochastic differential equation dR, = —dt+ dw, Rt and starts at a position Ro = x > 0. Explain what characteristics mean that this process can never be negative.",
