    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "The crucial aspect of such problems is to think about the symmetries. Here we have two time steps of equal length. The distri- bution of X(2) - X(1) is equal to that of X(1) - X(0) and it is a Brownian motion, so they are independent. We must have that the sign of X(2) - X(1) is negative which occurs with probability 1/2. We must also have that |X (2) - X(1)| > |X(1)| = |[X(1) - X(0)]- Since they have the same distribution, this occurs with probability 1/2, and the answer is 1/4. Here are some possible related questions: e What properties of Brownian motion make this answer work? e If a Brownian motion starts at zero, what is the probability that it is positive at both time 1 and 2? O",
