    "explanation": "We present a solution in C++. We use a simple array class from the xlw project but you could use any reasonable vector class. double Simulate(const MyArray& p, const MyArray& v, double u) \\{ int i=0; while ( u > p[il) \\{ u-= pLil; ++i; \\} return v[il; \\} Essentially, we want to find the first 7 such that the cumulative up to 7 is bigger than u. Rather than computing all the cumulatives, we instead subtract the probability of each event until we get something sufficiently small. Note that the timing of this algorithm is O(V) where N is the number of possible events. The memory usage is constant. Here are some possible related questions: e Suppose N is very big, how would you get a faster algorithm? e How would you test this algorithm? e Give an algorithm to generate a uniformly distributed random variable from an integer random number generator. e What is your favourite integer random number generator? e What problems can arise when using random number generators? O\n\n5. NUMERICAL TECHNIQUES AND ALGORITHMS",
