    "explanation": "Here's a simple solution in C++: void MakeHistogram(std: :vector<double>& BucketLefts, std: :vector<int>& BucketContents, const std::vector<double>& values, int number0fBuckets) \\{\n\ndouble minValue = *std: :min_element (values.begin(), values.end()); double maxValue = *std::max_element (values.begin(), values.end()); double bucketSize = (maxValue - minValue) /(Coumber0fBuckets-1); BucketLefts.resize (numberO0fBuckets) ; for (int i=0; i < numberOfBuckets; ++i) BucketLefts[i] = minValue + bucketSize*i; BucketContents.resize (number0fBuckets) ; for (int i=0; i < values.size(); ++i) \\{ int k = static_cast<int>(floor((values [i] - minValue)/bucketSize) ); ++BucketContents [k] ; \\} + The main subtleties are in choosing where to place the buckets. This is done by taking the leftmost point to be the minimum value and the left-hand-side of the rightmost bucket to be the maximum value. We assign a given value to a bucket simply by dividing its distance from the minimum by the size of a bucket. Note that this is a constant time algorithm but relies heavily on the fact that the buckets are of uniform size. Here are some possible related questions: e Can you suggest more sophisticated algorithms for bucket locations?\n\n5. NUMERICAL TECHNIQUES AND ALGORITHMS e If we allow non-uniform buckets, how would you assign a number to a bucket? e Modify the routine so its stores the mean value of numbers in a bucket as well as the number of items in a bucket. Do a two-dimensional analogue. O",
