    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "The key to this one is to observe that if you can scan from the left and reach a cluster of numbers that makes the running sum negative then that cluster will never be part of the maximal subarray. This means that you can start anew after it. So we can scan from the left, summing as we go, keeping a note of the maximal sum so far and its location. If we ever go negative, we start again. This is called Kadane's algorithm. If you are asked this question in an interview and decide to admit to having seen it before, you will gain by being able to name the algorithm. We present C++ code using classes from the xlw project. MyArray Kadane(const MyArray& input) \\{ double maximum = -1e100; double left = 0;\n\n5. NUMERICAL TECHNIQUES AND ALGORITHMS double right = 0; double currentMax =0; unsigned long currentLeft=0; for (unsigned long currentRight = 0; currentRight < input.size(); ++currentRight \\{ currentMax += input[currentRight]; if (currentMax > maximum) \\{ maximum = currentMax; left = currentLeft; right = currentRight; \\} if (currentMax < 0) \\{ currentMax =0; currentLeft = currentRight+1; \\} \\} MyArray results(3); results(0] = maximum; results[1] = left; results[2] = right; return results; \\}\n\nHere are some possible related questions: e What will happen if all entries are negative? e What do you think should happen if all entries are negative? O",
    "createdAt": "2026-05-27T03:07:21.649Z",
    "updatedAt": "2026-05-27T03:07:21.649Z"
