    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "The general principle here is that we can find the area of any set by computing the expectation of the indicator function of the set after enclosing it in a square (or cube). That is we find what proportion of points drawn from the square at random lie in the set. We compute the area of a circle with radius 1/2 centred at (1/2, 1/2) and multiply by 4, since the area is given by A=nr'. To compute the area, repeatedly draw pairs of independent uniforms from (0, 1] x [0,1], and measure what fraction land inside the circle (that is, if your uniforms are U; and U2, check that (U, - 1/2) + (U2 - 1/2)? < 1). This will converge to 7/4 at a rate of n - 1/2 by the Central Limit theorem.\n\n6. MATHEMATICS Here are some possible related questions: e Do you think this a good way to numerically approximate 7? e Prove that the rate of convergence is n\\sim 1/?. e What is Monte Carlo good for? e How would you approximate a if you had to find it to 100 decimal places? O",
