    "promptZh": "Implement strcmp.",
    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "The function strcmp compares two C-style strings and returns less than a negative number if the first is less than the second, zero if they agree and a positive number if the second is bigger. We define “less than” in a lexicographic sense, i.e. which one would be first in a dictionary? The function signature is therefore int strcmp( const char *stri, const char *str2 );\n\n7. CODING IN C++ The correct way to do this problem is, of course, to use the implementation from the C standard library in “String.h”. However, the interviewer is probably not looking for that solution and one should always give interviewers what they want, no matter how silly. The crucial fact here is that that C-style strings are zero terminated. Here's a simple implementation: int mystrcmp( const char *stri, const char *str2 ) \\{ while (*stri != '\\0? && *str2 != °\\0'? && *stri == *str2) \\{ ++str1; ++str2; \\} if (*stri < * str2) return -1; if (*stri > * str2) return 1; return 0; \\} Note that although the pointers point to const they are not const themselves. We can therefore increment them. We keep doing so until one string end is reached or a letter differs. We use pre-increment rather than post-increment since it is supposed to be faster. Here are some possible related questions: e How would you implement a case-insensitive comparison operator? e How do you convert a C++ string into a C-style string? What are the dangers in doing so? i)",
