    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "There are three main storage areas for variables in C++: e the heap; e the stack; e the data segment. Static variables are stored in the data segment, all the memory and locations for each variable are assigned before the program starts. They are not necessarily initialized, however, until their declaration is reached in the code. The heap is used for dynamically allocated memory, e.g. anything allocated using new or malloc. The stack is used for ordinary (automatic) variables. Here are some possible related questions: e When are static variables destroyed? e Give an example of whena static variable would be useful. O",
