    "source": "red-book",
    "sourceUrl": "红宝书 Quant Job Interview Questions And Answers",
    "sourceType": "book",
    "bookSlug": "red-book",
    "bookName": "红宝书 Quant Job Interview Questions And Answers",
    "visibility": "public",
    "promptEn": "Find the smallest subset of integers that you can use to produce 1,2,...,40 by only using \"+\" or \"-\" (each number in the subset can be used at most one time) .",
    "promptZh": "Find the smallest subset of integers that you can use to produce 1,2,...,40 by only using \"+\" or \"-\" (each number in the subset can be used at most one time) .",
    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "First, we derive a lower bound on how many numbers we need. If we have k numbers, we can use each of them in three different ways. We can therefore create 3k different numbers. However, note that one of the numbers must be zero, and for every positive number we can also create its negative.\n\nTo make numbers 1 through N, we must therefore have 3° >2N +1, For the case we are interested in, we need 3% > 81, sok > 4. To see that it can be done with 4, we work explicitly. If we start with 1 then we can get - 1,0,1. To be able to get 2, we must add in 3, we can then get - 4, —3, —2, -1,0,1, 2,3, 4. To obtain 5 without any overlaps, we can use 9. We can then get - 13, —12, —11, —10,...,10,11, 12, 13. Clearly, the next choice will be 27, and with it we can get all numbers from 1 to 40. Here are some possible related questions: e What if we need to construct 1 through 50? e What if we can use each number twice? e Can you think of a physical application? O",
    "createdAt": "2026-05-27T03:07:21.649Z",
    "updatedAt": "2026-05-27T03:07:21.649Z"
